Hi Ricky,

Good to see you this afternoon - I found our discussion really helpful.

As discussed, here is the preliminary discussion I had with Salifu from People's Dialogue. Nothing is confirmed and we're a long way off actually installing any sensors, but I wanted to get in touch with him relatively soon after the Accra meeting so that he would still have a rough idea what we're doing.

As you will read, he suggests focusing on the Sahara community in Adabraka. This might make a good pilot area for the imagery analysis.

If we do install sensors these will measure water level in a watercourse (e.g. river, stream, drain). I would have to discuss the monitoring strategy with Wouter, but we would probably install an array of sensors along a network. Amongst other things, this would help us to identify the time it takes for water within the network to rise for a given input of rain within the catchment.

From our point of view, a map of the drainage network would help us to identify the size of the catchment (i.e. the area over which water flows to a particular point) and possibly places where flooding is likely to occur. If we could somehow combine the imagery analysis with a way to predict where litter is likely to more prevalent then this could help us identify particular locations where blockages are likely to occur. Just to reiterate, the digital elevation model



